[{"id":"VR252105","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"direction_paragraph\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">Show all your work. Indicate clearly the methods you use, because you will be scored on the correctness of your methods as well as on the accuracy and completeness of your results and explanations.</p><br/><div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"passage\"><div class=\"prose style:1\"><p class=\"passage_para\">A nutritionist is interested in investigating the health habits of residents of a certain large town. The nutritionist stood at the end of the bottled water aisle of a local grocery store and asked residents to respond to the question, “Do you usually drink at least <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"24\"><math alttext=\"24\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>24</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> ounces of water per day?”</p></div></div></div></div><div class=\"item_part part_id:a part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"a\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(a) Explain how the nutritionist’s sampling method might have introduced bias and describe how the bias might affect the point estimate of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"p\"><math alttext=\"p\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, the proportion of all residents from the town who would respond “yes” to the question.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252105_rubric"},{"id":"VR252105","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:b part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"b\">\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Suppose that <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"38%\"><math alttext=\"38%\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>38</mn><mo>%</mo></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> of residents from the town drink at least <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"24\"><math alttext=\"24\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>24</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> ounces of water per day. Let <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"W\"><math alttext=\"W\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>W</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> represent the total number of residents selected at random, one at a time, from the town when the first resident who drinks at least <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"24\"><math alttext=\"24\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>24</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> ounces of water per day is selected. The graph shows the probability distribution of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"W\"><math alttext=\"W\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>W</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>.</p>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a graph with 15 bars. The horizontal axis is labeled W, and the numbers 1 through 15, in increments of 1, are indicated. The vertical axis is labeled “Probability,” and the numbers 0.00 through 0.40, in increments of 0.05, are indicated. Each number along the horizontal axis has one bar. The data represented by the bars are as follows.  W, 1. Probability, 0.380. W, 2. Probability 0.236. W, 3. Probability, 0.146. W, 4. Probability, 0.091. W, 5. Probability 0.056. W, 6. Probability, 0.035. W, 7. Probability, 0.022. W, 8. Probability, 0.013. W, 9. Probability, 0.008. W, 10. Probability, 0.005. W, 11. Probability, 0.003. W, 12. Probability, 0.002. W, 13. Probability, 0.001. W, 14. Probability, 0.001. W, 15. Probability, 0.000.\" height=\"248\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR252105.g01.png\" width=\"600\" /></div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(b) Calculate and interpret the expected value of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"W\"><math alttext=\"W\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>W</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>.</p>\n</div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252105_rubric"},{"id":"VR252105","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:c part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"c\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(c) Describe a simulation process that could be conducted to estimate the value of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"the probability of, open parenthesis, W is less than or equal to 3, close parenthesis\"><math alttext=\"the probability of, open parenthesis, W is less than or equal to 3, close parenthesis\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>P</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>W</mi><mo>≤</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252105_rubric"},{"id":"VR252105","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:d part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"d\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">A fitness instructor at a gym in the town is interested in examining whether the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"500\"><math alttext=\"500\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>500</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> members of the gym have different health habits from the overall population of residents of the town. A random sample of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"40\"><math alttext=\"40\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>40</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> members will be selected from the gym and each member will be asked to report whether they usually drink at least <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"24\"><math alttext=\"24\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>24</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> ounces of water per day.</p><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(d) If the instructor uses a <span class=\"formatted_text text_decoration:underline\">stratified</span> random sampling procedure to select the sample, identify an effective variable on which to stratify. Explain your reasoning.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252105_rubric"},{"id":"VR252105","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:e part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"e\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Assume the conditions for inference are met. A <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"98\"><math alttext=\"98\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>98</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> percent confidence interval for the proportion of all members from this gym who would report that they usually drink at least <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"24\"><math alttext=\"24\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>24</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> ounces of water per day was computed to be <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"0.375 plus or minus 0.178\"><math alttext=\"0.375 plus or minus 0.178\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>0.375</mn><mo>±</mo><mn>0.178</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>.</p><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(e) Does the confidence interval provide convincing statistical evidence that members of this gym have different health habits from the overall population of residents of the town? Justify your answer.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252105_rubric"}]